column1: BROAN Electric Radiant Ceiling Heater 157
column4: ['the product shown is not what I received.  the illustration is the wire coil unit and the 157 is a solid core heat unit, kinda like an electric stove top.  I have not used it enough to know if it works as well as the coiled wire.  It takes longer to heat up than the coil type.  I am unsure what happens if the unit overheats.  It has some type of thermal overload resistor, but not sure if it will reset like the thermal unit on the coil type.also my unit had been opened and was missing a screw and the center name plate, but I was able to use those parts from the old unit I was replacing.', 'The heater was purchased to replace an old model ceiling heater.  This one, manufactured by Broan, is installed in an elevator.  Normally, elevators are placed inside the building for use and uses the ambient air to heat/cool the space.  This particular elevator is installed on an outside wall and ambient temperatures are hard to come by.The Broan unit is turned on during the fall/winter season and runs almost constantly.  It keeps the elevator well heated.  The installation of the unit is very simple and can readily be installed over a 4x4 electrical box.  After the unit has been in use for awhile, the metal screen covering may begin to rattle.  There is a single phillips-head screw that holds the screen on.  This screw will loosen and requires tightening periodically.  Another alternative is to use a "Lock-Tite" product to secure the screw.  I\'ve tried using lock washers, but they do not hold very well.Overall, the unit is durable.  The small motor that rotates the fan needs to be cleaned and lubricated periodically.  At times, I\'ve found the fan speed slowing down and have had to clean/lubricate the motor to get the fan up to speed.  If the fan motor decreases too much, there is a thermal heat sensor that will cause the heater element to turn off.  This prevents the heater element to overheat and cause a fire.  Overall, a decent little unit that thats the chill off the space during the winter months.  Because of my search for this product, I purchased two of them.  One of them is in \'bench stock\' in case the first one should fail.', 'Don\'t know why I waited so long to purchase and install a ceiling heater in our Master Bath.  After one week of use, I am very pleased and hoping that it will provide many years of service and comfort.  I was disappointed to discover that there was no  installation  hardware included with the fan.  The instructions indicated that it was  "easy to install" - only if you have your own hardware available.', 'I bought this to replace a Broan model 154 that lasted about 2 years.  So far it works great.  It heats the bathroom nicely and is much quieter because it has a solid metal heating element instead of the thin coiled wire element of the model 154.  This type of element should be more efficient and last longer as well, but only time will tell.', 'Installed it overhead just as I step out of the shower. Works on a timer that I set for approx. 10 minutes. The family likes it also.', 'Improved design replaced old one like it that stopped working after several years', 'This device stopped working in a week after installation. The power to the heater tested good.', "Love this little heater, just renivating my Mum's home.   It's so nice to have this little heater in the basement bath.  Very reasonable in price and a nice touch!!!", 'Brand new unused, unopened.  Excellent purchase. ', 'The Broan 157 ceiling heater is a great upgrade from the " twisted wire element " heater. This unit has a solid element like on a stove top burner and heats my bathroom better.  You will be very happy with this unit.']

column4: ["This heater is fairly large.  Don't expect it to fit under your legs in the bleachers.  The handle is really handy, but makes it pretty tall.This heater is very versatile. It can be like the smaller versions with just one element on at half power, full power, or both elements on full power.  It goes through propane about the same as all the other ones I've seen, and full power is a lot of power.  The fan (powered by D cells) blows warm air in your direction, which is nice because otherwise it just goes straight up.IMHO it's way handier than the smaller bottle mounted version because it doesn't tip easily and it's not as tall.  It puts the heat in a better location.It's not a small heater, but is powerful, well built, and looks like it will last.", 'this id the 2nd one I have owned  first one was 5 years old and used every day it was cold it keeps our coach warm enough on low  and very economicl to run do recomend getting the hose with regolator and using a 20 pound bbq grill tank outside  and keeping a couple of the one pound throw aways in reserve incase of a midnight run out of gas senero , teriffic for those emergencies and blizzards requires no electric to run just a couple batteries to run the fan but will still  produce  het with out fan not operating . has the o2 depletion piliot light that lifts off if o2 level gets to low plus tip switch incase it gets tipped over by accident , Like any heating device care should be taken to assure you are opperating it in a safe manner and following the instructions that states the clearences on ll sides ', 'Current house furnace is out and this unit has filled in amazingly well.  Live in MN and have 2 of these with a couple electric room heaters for 2000 sqft plus home and been heating for a month.  Do recommend the 20# Walmart propane tanks w/ gauge for $48 and conversion hose to unit for more economical heating that the small canisters.  CAn heat for nearly a week.  Have CO monitor and never have had it go off once.  They are made to be CO free .  We do not leave them running when not home for safety reason but never yet had an issue.  ', 'I bought this to be able to work in my 2 car garage during cold days. It works very well. The only drawback I could see is that the fan moves very little air. Otherwise, I would have given it a 5 star rating....  Made the garage able to be worked in with no jacket in about 2 hours (on a 15 degree day)  Well worth it...   And would be great thing to have if an ice storm hits and the power (heat) went out...  Costs less than a buck an hour worth of propane to run on High.  I bought a 15 lb tank and ran it for about 18 hours.....    I plan on getting a couple of portable 1 lb bottles and a refill adapter.....', 'Got Mr. Heater for a heater in my outside work area and as an emergency backup heater in case of power failure in a storm or the heat pump went bad in middle of winter. Works perfect and am using hooked up to 20lb propane tank and also little 1lb tanks. Either way is working perfect.  This thing will run you out of house on 18,000 btu setting.  Always vent from a window or door to keep oxygen fresh and will be good for indoor use, you will still be plenty warm and no worries about any pipes freezing. Great product', "This little heater is just the ticket for quickly warming up our home on those chilly mornings. ,I live where we seldom get any colder than 40 degrees at night , we don't run any heater at night for safety reasons ,although I feel this heater is safer than any electric one , no cords to overheat . I turn it on in the morning and in 15 minutes the chill is taken off the house. I use a small fan to circulate the heat more than the one that comes with the heater which is efficient for one room.  I also purchased the 12 foot hose and regulator so I can hook to a 30 lbs bottle out side the house. just ran the hose through an existing tv cable  hole. I can get about a week of heat out of one bottle at 16.00 to refill. That is much cheaper than running electric space heaters.", "The dogs and I have a very comfortable warm environment now that the heater is able to be used. They are so happy that the inside of the motorhome is a lot more comfortable. We have been having nights that are in the upper twenties and low 30s so we're really grateful to have a heater the prize this my cheat on low setting it it basically heats the Whole 30 ft motorhome it generates more than enough heat on low and will run for a hundred hours on that setting .  It is very warm at got my  farm in Coupeville Washington. thanks a lot for a great item!!", 'I\'ve been hunting deer for 42 years now and never worried about the cold weather when I was younger, mostly because pop-up portable blinds and portable heaters like these were not available back then. But my youngest daughter started hunting with me 6 years ago and after watching her brave a particularly cold opening day her first year I decided there had to be a better setup so she could enjoy going with me and I could insure I would get to continue to enjoy spending such moments with her, so I bought my first ground blind and my first Mr. Heater Little Buddy heater, and closing weekend of rifle season was soooooo much more enjoyable. Having a heat source to warm our feet made all the difference in the world being able to sit beside my daughter and just watch her scan our surroundings for her first deer, and did she take a beauty! After realizing how great the difference in the experience having shelter and heat made, I broke down and bought blinds for my Dad, nephew, and great friend who owns the property where we hunt, and then decided everyone should be able to stay warm and enjoy their time in the field as well, so I retired my Little Buddy heater and bought three of the Buddy heaters and one of the heater/cooker models and stocked each blind with a heater. The difference between the Little Buddy and the bigger Buddy models is very noticeably different! Running the bigger Buddy heaters warmed up a two person ground blind sufficiently enough to allow us to take off our coats, even with several windows open, and sit comfortably without creating undue noise or alerts to the deer as we watched many feed and browse around in the field in front of us. Hunting went from a cold and trying event to a greatly enjoyed experience spending time with my daughter, my Dad, my nephew, and friend! I\'ve always said a bad day hunting or fishing is better than a good day working anytime, but having Mr. Heater Buddy heaters warming our ground blinds has made such a difference in our time spent together so much more enjoyable that now my oldest daughter is joining in, and that alone made any expense paid for the equipment one of my best investments! Funny story: My Dad was using the heater I put in the blind he was using and after spending the morning hunting we all went to breakfast and I asked him how well he liked having heat, and his reply was, "great for about 20 minutes and then the damned thing quit and wouldn\'t re-light!" I asked him if he had opened any windows and he said "no, it wasn\'t light yet so I was just enjoying staying warm, until the heater went out!" I started laughing and he was taken aback by my reaction and asked why I was laughing, had I played a joke and given him the junk heater? I said no and told him he should be thankful Mr. Heater saved his life! Not knowing what I was referring to he had a puzzled look on his face, so I told him that the heater has a low oxygen sensor built into it and because he had the windows closed up fresh air could not circulate through the blind and the heater shut off before he could pass out from carbon monoxide poisoning! The look on his face was priceless! All he could say was "glad someone was looking out for him." After breakfast and getting some chores done we all went back to our blinds and my Dad made sure he opened some windows and lit the heater, and spent the rest of the day happy and warm. Moral of the story: The safety features built into Mr. Heater heaters work! Excellent design, quality built, and smart safety features all make Mr. Heater heaters great products you can trust and that make experiences during cold weather so much more enjoyable, and if having one gets a friend or family member to join in the fun, that\'s money well spent! Not to mention having the added insurance of staying warm at home should the power go out for an extended period of time during cold weather!   So, that\'s my experience with Mr. Heater heaters, and I can and do highly recommend to anyone needing and looking for a quality and dependable portable small heater, get one. You will be glad you did! ', 'Due to recently power outage frequently, I brought this protable heater for indoor use for emergency. I did not have chance to try it for hour long but I did try and find out it is very practical make and workable. Only issue to me is I don‚Äôt aware it need 4 D battery to run and how long one will last.Any how it is a very good product,I highly recommend it.', "Will be able to use it in my fish house, heat my area that I use for skinning and tanning the furs that I've trapped.  Like the fact that I can hook up to a larger propane tank.  The fan is a bonus and the 3 different heating levels are great also."]

column1: Dr. Heater DR966 240-volt Hardwired Shop or Home Garage Commercial Heater
column4: ['The heater requires a 35A circuit with #8AWG wire per Article 424 of the National Electric Code. The heater only pulls 25A on highest setting, but is considered a "fixed" device with a "continuous load", so the wiring and breaker need to be rated at 125%.  That puts it at 31.25A, over a #10AWG wire and 30A breaker\'s rating.  Don\'t risk your insurance company denying your claim if something goes wrong.At that power, you don\'t want to use a line voltage thermostat designed for smaller baseboard heaters.  If you want a wall mounted thermostat, look into any conventional thermostat, a 24VAC HVAC transformer, and a 40A 2-pole 24V HVAC contactor.  I have three DR-966 heaters with their built-in thermostats all the way up and their switches on the 6000W setting, running off a single 24V transformer and Hunter 429999B thermostat, with a contactor near each heater switching the 240V AC on and off.  If I\'m not in the building I keep the thermostat at its minimum 45 degrees setting to prevent pipes from freezing.  Using a contactor, you\'re essentially automating turning the heater on and off, no different than using the instruction manual\'s method of using the circuit breaker, and not voiding any warranty.This is not an infrared heater, the manufacturer calls itself both Dr. Heater and Dr. Infrared Heater.  The heater is a wire coil type, the front two coils are 1500 watts each tied together, the rear coil is a single 3000 watt for a total of 6000 watts.  With the fan blowing on them, a spiral or two of the rear coil may get red, primarily near the coil supports.  If the fan doesn\'t turn the coil will get red hot, and probably break the support wire inside and then droop.  I received one heater that had a bent fan bracket not allowing the blade to turn and when powered up the rear coil did just that.  I received a refund to buy a third heater and since the vendor was filing a damage claim, was told to discard the defective heater if after 10 days the shipping carrier didn\'t contact me to inspect it.  After the 10 days passed without being contacted, I straightened the bracket out, verified the fan worked and then adjusted the drooping rear coil so there was a minimum of red spots.  I ended up with 3 heaters for the price of 2.Although the output of the heaters may feel like no more than a hand held hair dryer when your area is cold, follow the instruction manual\'s recommendations of keeping it the proper distances from walls and other objects.  If you feel it isn\'t putting out like it should, use a clamp-on ammeter to verify the heater is drawing around 25A on each leg with the temperature control fully clockwise and the switch on 6000W.  If it\'s not, contact the vendor.I have a 30x50 pole barn shop with a 10\' ceiling, so the roof peak is about 12\'.  It has "double bubble foil" insulation on the walls and roof, with exposed trusses.  The heater\'s manual recommends 1.25 watts of heating per cubic foot, so 30\' x 50\' x 11\' x 1.25W = 20,625 watts.  With 18,000W of heaters, I can set the thermostat at 60, go to the home store 10 miles away and by the time I get back the heaters have shut off.  If I already have my materials and I\'m in a hurry to get started, I supplement the electrics with a 3-burner 45,000 BTU tank-mounted propane heater to raise the temp to 60 faster.  So a single 6000W heater in an uninsulated 3-car garage may not be adequate.Before I contacted the eBay vendor about the damaged heater, I contacted the Dr. Heater by phone.  They told me they would send a replacement heater and pre-paid shipping label.  Then I received an email stating they would email me a label within one business day and start the replacement process.  I never received the label by email.  When I called Dr. Heater on the second business day they said they would email a label by the end of the day.  I never got that, so I resolved the issue with the eBay vendor, a 10 star solution.  So it may not be worth the stamp to send in your warranty card.  If you get a working unit, it\'s worth the money.  Good luck repairing one later, since parts don\'t seem to be available.  Due to one of mine having a bent fan bracket, if you get a DR-966 in the 160014xx serial number range, stick a screwdriver in the back and try to spin the fan blade before installation.  A pallet of these might have gotten dropped on the dock after coming off a ship from China.  If that bracket was bent before the heater was assembled, then don\'t trust the QC sticker on the back. It hasn\'t got to zero outside yet, and I haven\'t got my first electric bill, so I may be in for a shock in that respect.', "It's an OK heater. You MUST user the heavy 8 gauge wire and the 35 amp circuit breakers that the instructions say. It has a much quieter fan than my old one, so that's a really nice thing. Puts out a good amount of heat for a small heater. So Great so far? The only bad thing that I have to say about it, is the same as a couple other reviews. The thermostat just doesn't work right. It turns on at 65 degrees and cycles on and off like you would expect. But during the day it keeps turning on more and more warming up the shop by turning on at higher and higher temps. By the end of the day it was turning on at 79 degrees and this was with the thermostat not being moved, set the same all day long. So if it had a better thermostat it would easily be a 5 Star heater. Better yet a remote mounted thermostat would be Great! Heats up my well insulated shop 20X16X8 even when it dropped to zero outside. So it's a GREAT heater with a crappy thermostat.         ", 'Installed this heater on a 20 degree day in a dairy milk house ( block building). It had that space up 65 degrees in 20 minutes.This was at the full 6000 watts. Then left the thermostat at 3/4. This was adequate for me. Maybe 70 degrees at full power? A really quality unit for price!', '1000 square foot shop stays warm when it‚Äôs 30 degrees outside. I keep the temp about 58 to 60 when working. Any warmer and it‚Äôs not comfortable. Fairly quite on high.  Great value on a heater. Propane was costly and dangerous in a shop using flammable liquids. ', 'I got this as an open box, but looks brand new.  Got it for a great price.  I have it on a 30 amp breaker with #10 wire.  Seems to work very well with no issues.', 'Nice heater for its size...Puts out a fair amount of heat.Will probably consume a fair amount of electricity if my calculations are right', "This is a well built product at a reasonable price. It is easy to install. It cycles properly and maintains the temperature in my 24'X24' garage. I was expecting more fan noise but it is fairly  quiet.", 'Its a good product for the money', 'Does a good job heating my garage/wood shop.Some mentioned a need to upgrade the electrical capacity. I have a 30 amp breaker with #10 gauge wire. Recommendations are 8 gauge with a 35 amp breaker.I decided to check the amp load of the heater before upgrading. I wired it up and put my clamp meter on both legs at high power. Reading was 21-22 amps per leg. 10 gauge wire is rated for 30 amps. I now run the heater on low when not present in the shop. I switch to high only when I‚Äôm in the shop if necessary.No problems at all. Puts out the heat when I need it.Anyway, I do plan on upgrading wiring and breaker when the weather warms up.Good heater, good price.', "Heater  works great. Its keeping my shop comfortably warm without busting hot air on you like some other heaters I've used."]

column1: BROAN Electric Radiant Ceiling Heater 157
column4: ['the product shown is not what I received.  the illustration is the wire coil unit and the 157 is a solid core heat unit, kinda like an electric stove top.  I have not used it enough to know if it works as well as the coiled wire.  It takes longer to heat up than the coil type.  I am unsure what happens if the unit overheats.  It has some type of thermal overload resistor, but not sure if it will reset like the thermal unit on the coil type.also my unit had been opened and was missing a screw and the center name plate, but I was able to use those parts from the old unit I was replacing.', 'The heater was purchased to replace an old model ceiling heater.  This one, manufactured by Broan, is installed in an elevator.  Normally, elevators are placed inside the building for use and uses the ambient air to heat/cool the space.  This particular elevator is installed on an outside wall and ambient temperatures are hard to come by.The Broan unit is turned on during the fall/winter season and runs almost constantly.  It keeps the elevator well heated.  The installation of the unit is very simple and can readily be installed over a 4x4 electrical box.  After the unit has been in use for awhile, the metal screen covering may begin to rattle.  There is a single phillips-head screw that holds the screen on.  This screw will loosen and requires tightening periodically.  Another alternative is to use a "Lock-Tite" product to secure the screw.  I\'ve tried using lock washers, but they do not hold very well.Overall, the unit is durable.  The small motor that rotates the fan needs to be cleaned and lubricated periodically.  At times, I\'ve found the fan speed slowing down and have had to clean/lubricate the motor to get the fan up to speed.  If the fan motor decreases too much, there is a thermal heat sensor that will cause the heater element to turn off.  This prevents the heater element to overheat and cause a fire.  Overall, a decent little unit that thats the chill off the space during the winter months.  Because of my search for this product, I purchased two of them.  One of them is in \'bench stock\' in case the first one should fail.', 'Don\'t know why I waited so long to purchase and install a ceiling heater in our Master Bath.  After one week of use, I am very pleased and hoping that it will provide many years of service and comfort.  I was disappointed to discover that there was no  installation  hardware included with the fan.  The instructions indicated that it was  "easy to install" - only if you have your own hardware available.', 'I bought this to replace a Broan model 154 that lasted about 2 years.  So far it works great.  It heats the bathroom nicely and is much quieter because it has a solid metal heating element instead of the thin coiled wire element of the model 154.  This type of element should be more efficient and last longer as well, but only time will tell.', 'Installed it overhead just as I step out of the shower. Works on a timer that I set for approx. 10 minutes. The family likes it also.', 'Improved design replaced old one like it that stopped working after several years', 'This device stopped working in a week after installation. The power to the heater tested good.', "Love this little heater, just renivating my Mum's home.   It's so nice to have this little heater in the basement bath.  Very reasonable in price and a nice touch!!!", 'Brand new unused, unopened.  Excellent purchase. ', 'The Broan 157 ceiling heater is a great upgrade from the " twisted wire element " heater. This unit has a solid element like on a stove top burner and heats my bathroom better.  You will be very happy with this unit.']

column1: MR. HEATER 30-60,000 BTU Propane QBT Forced Air Heater F271370
column4: ['This Mr Heater is great.  I use it in a 1000 sqft shop and it warms it up in minutes.  I replaced a radiant kerosene heater and am glad I did.  Years ago I had a kerosene tube heater that was extremely loud but the Mr Heater is very quiet.  Highly recommend.', 'I am convinced ALL Mr Heater products are nothing buy JUNK!  Lights right up first time - worked for about 20 minutes.2nd use - lights right up - runs for 10 minutes shuts off - Re-light -works for 10 minutes - shuts off TRIED to re-light - no dice - boxed it back up and sent it back,This is not the first Mr Heater item I have had issue with -They use to make a quality product - something changed - LGB!', 'Dont heat up as everyone say. Ran it about an hour in my garage at 32f didnt get much warmer, maybe to 34 in an hour with door closed. Smelled like burned propane and my eyes were burning, had to shut it off it was so bad. Looks to me that people that review them on YouTube are people that sell them. Will be selling this heater get something electric. Would not recommend at all, i was very disappointed. ', 'Had it on low setting and thawed out all my frozen water pipes in a 2 bay garage that was under 10 degrees F. ', 'I recommend this heater.  It works well and heats up my shop quickly and easily.', 'This thing heats my garage in less than 5 minutes. I very impressed. Very happy with this purchase.', 'Great to use in a garage environment.', 'Good little heater. 400 sq foot garage. Gets it up to 80 easy.  , I have to turn it off to keep from sweating!! They should make them more efficient. A little costly if used a lot.', 'Set up is a cinch. Physical was smaller than expect which was a plus.  It is a bit noisy; but it raised the temperature in my 750 ft2 shop 30 degrees within a couple of hours. I will be getting another one for my garage and home. ', 'compact works great will take the chill out of 1200 square feet shop']

column1: Comfort Zone Electric Heater Furnace Safety Overheat Protection Ceiling Mount
column4: ["easy install, seems to be made well.  love the three heat settingsall parts were present and was packaged well. upon install, turned on power, turned thermostat knob and bam...had instant heat as I had expected...bring on the cold!!.however, one feature that I wish it had was a delayed fan off to cool the heating coils after use. when you rotate the thermostat knob, the fan shuts down immediately, leaving the hot coils to cool off too slowly. also, the unit I received didn't have a visible mark on the thermostat knob for easy identification of position (easily fixed). overall, nice product for the money", "So much easier than installing a gas furnace and vent.  Fan creates a full circular heat draft all the way around my 20x20 detached garage.  Heats up quickly and I can then turn it down.  Thermostat works well.  I had a 30 amp welder plug in a good location, so mounted it on the ceiling and used a 10' dryer plug cord.  Quick and easy installation.  Should have done this years ago.  No more freezing with a little space heater.", 'I recommend knowledg√§ble HVAC guy to add the external thermostat if you need one.  I have high ceilings and wanted to use my mouting system that √¢ttaches to the walls in a corner - no ceiling holes, but two nights of engineering the aluminum mounts.  Hester has been set on low since I installed it and let the Honeywell electronic thermost√¢t do the work.  Waiting for √£ heating bill to begin tuning it for optim√£l settings depending on weather.  But garage can get hot it works so well.', "I purchased this heater to use in a 666 sq ft, 4-car, uninsulated, vaulted ceiling garage.  Obviously this is meant to be used in a smaller, more insulated setting.  I wanted to try just one first, and then add as necessary.The heater itself seems to be well-built as far as structure, and designed well as far as installation and operation.  Including running wiring and building a wall mount (vaulted ceiling so no ceiling studs), it took 2-3hrs to get up and running.In my large uninsulated setting, over the course of 3-4hrs, it was able to raise the temperature from 25*F to 45*F, roughly speaking.  In other words, from intolerable to tolerable.  Which is about what I expected from it.  I think it would do quite well at maintaining a higher temperature if I were to use my propane 'salamander' to initially heat the space.Based on other's reviews and my own experience, there seems to be a major quality control concern in the assembly line for these regarding the fan nut.  I was unaware of this until after it was installed, but I'm almost certain I have the same issue as almost everyone else.  Before mounting the heater there was a nut and washer rattling around inside.  After a semi-thorough check, I figured it was an erroneous leftover.  Having read the reviews and after hearing a small rattle when the heater runs, I will be dismounting and tearing it down to install that nut properly.  This is both an inconvenience and really a potential danger.  For that I've removed a star from the rating.That being said, I will be purchasing another one, possibly two more.  Can't beat the price to performance ratio anywhere.Edit from the future:  I bought another one, slightly updated since the first.  This one had no problems and even runs quieter.  Awesome.", "This heater does a great job heating my 24'x30' insulated shop. I have it on a Honeywell line thermostat, and typically keep it at 40* to keep water lines from freezing, but when I'm ready to work in the ship I just turn it up and in 20 minutes it's nice and toasty. The other day it was 30* outside, but on high this ran for less than 5 minutes every 20-30 minutes.The only potential negative to be aware of is that it has a slight whistle when it's running. It's enough that I think about it every time it starts up, but it's not enough to be a nuisance.Overall I'm very happy with my purchase; it was easy to install, and is cost-effective for the job I needed it to do.", "Fast shipping.Well packaged.All metal construction.Enough detail in instructions,easily installed,best of all:heater works great.No issues so far.I heat a decent size 2 car garage and this is all I need.Recomend a ceiling fan to force the heat down,same thing with all of 'em.I can not stand beneath this heater when it is on high,it is way beyond my expectations.It is not very big or impressive,but do not let that part fool ya,it is a good heater.I have left the thermostat inside the heater,so far this is working fine.", 'I have used 4 times now and I really like it. If you have a insulated two car garage this heater will do the job nicely.It only took about 30 minutes to go from 30¬∞ to  62¬∞ in an hour it was 71¬∞ had to turn it down to work though. I like it 57¬∞ to 63¬∞ when working on a project. This heater is perfect for my needs. Little less than $100 too!üëç', "I'm happy with this heater and wish I'd found it years ago. I installed it in my basement workshop and it is way better than the big baseboard heater and kerosene heater I'd been using for many years. It's quiet and easy to install and heats the basement better than I'd anticipated. The workmanship and quality are great and I especially like that the sheet metal parts are post painted as opposed to crummy pre-paint and so all the sheet metal cut edges and corners are painted and nice and smooth and burr free.", 'I use this heater turned down low just to knock the edge off the cold so I can work comfortably in my 3 car garage shop.  I have it set on about 1/3 of its capacity and it keeps the garage at about 55- 60, the way I like it.  If I were to turn it up on high it would make the garage toasty warm.  The installation was straight forward and simple.  I bought a plug, 15 ft. of 10-3 service cord and a cord grip to make the installation. I plug it into my 220 volt welder receptacle when I want to have heat.  Wish I had found it years ago.', 'Great heat output, replaced my floor oil heater and small plug in with this one.  Only reason I gave it a 4 not 5 is that # 1 the fan blade was loose when I got it and the simple mechanism makes a rattling noise that is not necessary.  It only has a moving fan part but is kinda noisy.  Heats very well.']

column1: Mr Heater Big Buddy Portable Propane Heater 18,000 BTU Swivel regulators Quiet
column4: ["This heater is fairly large.  Don't expect it to fit under your legs in the bleachers.  The handle is really handy, but makes it pretty tall.This heater is very versatile. It can be like the smaller versions with just one element on at half power, full power, or both elements on full power.  It goes through propane about the same as all the other ones I've seen, and full power is a lot of power.  The fan (powered by D cells) blows warm air in your direction, which is nice because otherwise it just goes straight up.IMHO it's way handier than the smaller bottle mounted version because it doesn't tip easily and it's not as tall.  It puts the heat in a better location.It's not a small heater, but is powerful, well built, and looks like it will last.", 'this id the 2nd one I have owned  first one was 5 years old and used every day it was cold it keeps our coach warm enough on low  and very economicl to run do recomend getting the hose with regolator and using a 20 pound bbq grill tank outside  and keeping a couple of the one pound throw aways in reserve incase of a midnight run out of gas senero , teriffic for those emergencies and blizzards requires no electric to run just a couple batteries to run the fan but will still  produce  het with out fan not operating . has the o2 depletion piliot light that lifts off if o2 level gets to low plus tip switch incase it gets tipped over by accident , Like any heating device care should be taken to assure you are opperating it in a safe manner and following the instructions that states the clearences on ll sides ', 'Current house furnace is out and this unit has filled in amazingly well.  Live in MN and have 2 of these with a couple electric room heaters for 2000 sqft plus home and been heating for a month.  Do recommend the 20# Walmart propane tanks w/ gauge for $48 and conversion hose to unit for more economical heating that the small canisters.  CAn heat for nearly a week.  Have CO monitor and never have had it go off once.  They are made to be CO free .  We do not leave them running when not home for safety reason but never yet had an issue.  ', 'I bought this to be able to work in my 2 car garage during cold days. It works very well. The only drawback I could see is that the fan moves very little air. Otherwise, I would have given it a 5 star rating....  Made the garage able to be worked in with no jacket in about 2 hours (on a 15 degree day)  Well worth it...   And would be great thing to have if an ice storm hits and the power (heat) went out...  Costs less than a buck an hour worth of propane to run on High.  I bought a 15 lb tank and ran it for about 18 hours.....    I plan on getting a couple of portable 1 lb bottles and a refill adapter.....', 'Got Mr. Heater for a heater in my outside work area and as an emergency backup heater in case of power failure in a storm or the heat pump went bad in middle of winter. Works perfect and am using hooked up to 20lb propane tank and also little 1lb tanks. Either way is working perfect.  This thing will run you out of house on 18,000 btu setting.  Always vent from a window or door to keep oxygen fresh and will be good for indoor use, you will still be plenty warm and no worries about any pipes freezing. Great product', "This little heater is just the ticket for quickly warming up our home on those chilly mornings. ,I live where we seldom get any colder than 40 degrees at night , we don't run any heater at night for safety reasons ,although I feel this heater is safer than any electric one , no cords to overheat . I turn it on in the morning and in 15 minutes the chill is taken off the house. I use a small fan to circulate the heat more than the one that comes with the heater which is efficient for one room.  I also purchased the 12 foot hose and regulator so I can hook to a 30 lbs bottle out side the house. just ran the hose through an existing tv cable  hole. I can get about a week of heat out of one bottle at 16.00 to refill. That is much cheaper than running electric space heaters.", "The dogs and I have a very comfortable warm environment now that the heater is able to be used. They are so happy that the inside of the motorhome is a lot more comfortable. We have been having nights that are in the upper twenties and low 30s so we're really grateful to have a heater the prize this my cheat on low setting it it basically heats the Whole 30 ft motorhome it generates more than enough heat on low and will run for a hundred hours on that setting .  It is very warm at got my  farm in Coupeville Washington. thanks a lot for a great item!!", 'I\'ve been hunting deer for 42 years now and never worried about the cold weather when I was younger, mostly because pop-up portable blinds and portable heaters like these were not available back then. But my youngest daughter started hunting with me 6 years ago and after watching her brave a particularly cold opening day her first year I decided there had to be a better setup so she could enjoy going with me and I could insure I would get to continue to enjoy spending such moments with her, so I bought my first ground blind and my first Mr. Heater Little Buddy heater, and closing weekend of rifle season was soooooo much more enjoyable. Having a heat source to warm our feet made all the difference in the world being able to sit beside my daughter and just watch her scan our surroundings for her first deer, and did she take a beauty! After realizing how great the difference in the experience having shelter and heat made, I broke down and bought blinds for my Dad, nephew, and great friend who owns the property where we hunt, and then decided everyone should be able to stay warm and enjoy their time in the field as well, so I retired my Little Buddy heater and bought three of the Buddy heaters and one of the heater/cooker models and stocked each blind with a heater. The difference between the Little Buddy and the bigger Buddy models is very noticeably different! Running the bigger Buddy heaters warmed up a two person ground blind sufficiently enough to allow us to take off our coats, even with several windows open, and sit comfortably without creating undue noise or alerts to the deer as we watched many feed and browse around in the field in front of us. Hunting went from a cold and trying event to a greatly enjoyed experience spending time with my daughter, my Dad, my nephew, and friend! I\'ve always said a bad day hunting or fishing is better than a good day working anytime, but having Mr. Heater Buddy heaters warming our ground blinds has made such a difference in our time spent together so much more enjoyable that now my oldest daughter is joining in, and that alone made any expense paid for the equipment one of my best investments! Funny story: My Dad was using the heater I put in the blind he was using and after spending the morning hunting we all went to breakfast and I asked him how well he liked having heat, and his reply was, "great for about 20 minutes and then the damned thing quit and wouldn\'t re-light!" I asked him if he had opened any windows and he said "no, it wasn\'t light yet so I was just enjoying staying warm, until the heater went out!" I started laughing and he was taken aback by my reaction and asked why I was laughing, had I played a joke and given him the junk heater? I said no and told him he should be thankful Mr. Heater saved his life! Not knowing what I was referring to he had a puzzled look on his face, so I told him that the heater has a low oxygen sensor built into it and because he had the windows closed up fresh air could not circulate through the blind and the heater shut off before he could pass out from carbon monoxide poisoning! The look on his face was priceless! All he could say was "glad someone was looking out for him." After breakfast and getting some chores done we all went back to our blinds and my Dad made sure he opened some windows and lit the heater, and spent the rest of the day happy and warm. Moral of the story: The safety features built into Mr. Heater heaters work! Excellent design, quality built, and smart safety features all make Mr. Heater heaters great products you can trust and that make experiences during cold weather so much more enjoyable, and if having one gets a friend or family member to join in the fun, that\'s money well spent! Not to mention having the added insurance of staying warm at home should the power go out for an extended period of time during cold weather!   So, that\'s my experience with Mr. Heater heaters, and I can and do highly recommend to anyone needing and looking for a quality and dependable portable small heater, get one. You will be glad you did! ', 'Due to recently power outage frequently, I brought this protable heater for indoor use for emergency. I did not have chance to try it for hour long but I did try and find out it is very practical make and workable. Only issue to me is I don‚Äôt aware it need 4 D battery to run and how long one will last.Any how it is a very good product,I highly recommend it.', "Will be able to use it in my fish house, heat my area that I use for skinning and tanning the furs that I've trapped.  Like the fact that I can hook up to a larger propane tank.  The fan is a bonus and the 3 different heating levels are great also."]

column1: Dr. Infrared heater 3000W Greenhouse Garage Workshop Heater
column4: ["Bought this for my workshop in the winter.  It's only 12x12 but has very tall ceilings so I needed something that could heat the space adequately.  The unit is a lot smaller than I thought so that was a plus as it doesn't take up much room.You will need a 220V outlet which I had.  It doesn't heat the room super quick.  I usually turn it on 30 minutes before I'm going to work out there and it's good enough.  Can't expect much more from a unit so small.  The controls work well and so far it seems like a decent unit for the price.", "I originally bought this to heat my wife's greenhouse replacing two milk house heaters. This heater warmed her10x14 greenhouse so well and evenly that we don't need a second heater anymore and she had new growthon plants in the middle of last winter with snow on the ground. I liked it so well I bought another one for my work shop.", 'THE PLUG ABSOLUTELY WOULD NOT FIT INTO A STANDARD USA ELECTRICAL BOX ! ! ! !We really wanted the heater to be ready for the arrival of cold weather, and it was a huge shock to have to deal with re-fitting / re-placing the plug before we could get the heater and our Greenhouse ready.We had to competely replace the plug !     Once the plug had been replaced, it fit perfectly into our Electrician installed electrical box.The heater works really well, and we\'re very pleased with it.   However.... having to deal with a "retro-fit" before we could even get the heater plugged in was very disappointing, and caused quite a delay.', "A lot better than milkbox heaters. Got it late in the season ,Early Feb. I have an uninsulated 10x12 greenhouse and when it got down to 18 it kept it at set 50 degrees.. Didn't run as much as the milkbox unit.  . Havent got my electric bill yet so cant fully rate it and also hasent gone thru Dec. and Jan.", 'Great little heater, plugs into our 20 amp outlet for window ac. Puts out way more heat than our 110 volt infrared heaters, hope its easier on the electric bill??.  Once we have our outside wood boiler hooked up, this little heater will be used in the green house. Great heater for the money.A+A+A+', 'Perfect heater for my small work shop and model train layout.  It puts outmore than enough heat on cold winter days.  Thanks for a great product design.', 'Have not had to use yet but looks good and heats well.  Will know more when gets cold enough to need heat in greenhouse.', 'Works great', 'This heater heats very quickly.  It is designed to heat a greenhouse.']

column1: NEW MR HEATER F299710 BLUE FLAME LP GAS HEATER 10K VENT FREE 250 SQ FT 3311826
column4: ['Great heater, literally heats my whole home, the fan could be a little more powerful but does move a little air, this was a replacement for my pellet stove, during a power outage the pellet stove would not work, with this propane Mr. heater you still have heat during an outage just no blower operation ', "The pros are the price is reasonable and no special installations is requires. I can use my RV propane tanks, so the only extras I had to buy was a regulator and connector hose.  It puts out pretty good heat, and my CO detector doesn't go off. I use it in my 24 x 30 shop.The cons are it has an odor that gets pretty strong after an hour or more.  Additionally, if I don't open a window or crack a door, within 2 hours it depletes the oxygen in the room to the point it shuts down.  The oxygen gets so low my propane torch won't fire up.  The ventilation it requires to stay running lets a lot of cold air in, offsetting the heat it produces.", "This is just what we needed.  We are in a remote area of Maine where we tend to get power failures in winter.  This unit works great and doesn't depend on electricity to keep us warm.  This is important since we can reach temps of -30 degrees F.  Highly recommend this unit.", 'We heat both houses with only ventless blue flame products, 10k, 20k and 30k units. This 30k propane unit is the best we\'ve come across. Very clean burning and as attractive a casing as they come, and a thermostat that works . Our 30k mock "cast iron stove\' unit is very attractive but not as efficient. This is our second Mr. Heater and would definitely buy from BigDealOnTheHill again if they had one.', "I bought this for a small drafty cabin I rent. hook up was easy once I ran the steel pipe from the back porch under the cabin to where I put the heater. Installed a Mr. Heater regulator on the tank end of the pipe, a Mr. Heater shut off valve and flex pipe at the heater end.I also bought and installed the optional fan for it however the it dosent turn on when you set it to auto. But constant on is ok. The temp settings seem to work fine on the heater itself though, when I put the control knob on 1, 2, 3, or 4 it shuts down and fires back up when the temp gets to those levels, I don't know what those temps actually are but on setting 5 it runs contignously.", 'This is one of the best purchases I\'ve made.  Heats very evenly with no hotspots. Wouldn\'t waste the money on the fan option. A $20 oscillating 6" fan up high works perfectly', "This is the best thing I have purchased.  It is Awesome,  the pilot light is so easy to start. The most wonderful about it is the built-in thermostat.  I turns the flame on and off. This keeps the house warm without me having to turn the heat on and off. Now with Mr. Heater my furnace hardly kicks on.  I'm Happy ", "Yes hello I've tested this product as a backup heater for my home I live in California where they threaten to shut off our power supply and I believe it will be adequate for heating my home I like it. At a constant burn it's about 1 gallon / 3 hours.", 'I\'ve had one of these heater at a remote cabin where the nighttime temperatures sometime are 23F many times during the winter.  This model does a superb job of heating the entire cabin without having to turn it up above "medium".It is easy to use and I\'ve had for ten years without any need for maintenance. I bought an extra heater for another location.  I highly recommend this unit.', "This was the cheapest solution(sale $155.00) instead of me adding a fire place. With generator, gas or wood burning stove costing significantly more. My goal was two fold, heat up my connected 2 car garage when i work on my never quite finished project car, and have heat forbmy house just in case a power outage occurs. A week after I purchased the heater. During a minus 5 degree night, my old boiler goes out at 3 am. So Mr heater is brought to my living room and the boiler contracting company says they are experiencing heavy call volume an d doesn't know when a technician will be able to Get to there but it's within 24hrs. Long story short, 3 1/2 20gallon propane tanks over 27 hours from outage to boiler being fixed. My house was kept warm and no pipes froze. So it was a worth wild investment."]

column1: Lasko 5572 Room Heater
column4: ['I purchased the Lasko 5397 oscillating heater for my mom several years ago +- 5 YEARS AGO. She uses it almost year round because she is always cold. She lives in San Fransisco and if you know anything about Mark Twain you know he said the coldest winter he ever spent was a summer in S.F. She called me and informed me that the  \t5397  was making funny noises and had a weird smell. I went over and discovered that it was shorting out. While in the off mode, the top of the unit was getting hotter than it does when it is in use. I took it out of the house and replaced it with the Lasko 5572. I purchased it only a few days ago but already I can tell she likes it even better. The 5397 comes on a pedestal stand. This one pivots at the floor. Because it pivots at the floor, the heat reaches down further on her legs thus she is happier. Don\'t be fooled by the photo, the heating element does NOT come all the way down to the floor but it does come down further then the previous oscillating heater. Both models work great and both have a remote control but this one edges out the other just by the fact that it has a "longer" heating element. I love the fact that even when on for 4 hours at the highest setting, if she accidentally bumps up against it or brushes up against it she won\'t burn herself like she would with one of those dish looking heaters. You can touch ANY PART of these "Ceramic" heaters (while they are operational and functioning) and NOT burn yourself.', 'I have used a wood furnace for 30 years, but now to old to handle the wood. I purchased the Lasko 5572 heater to see if I could use it to help heat my house. As I had 220 baseboard heaters installed knowing I must give up the wood heat. I was totally supprised with the Lasko heater, it not only helped the baseboard heater,it took the place of the 220 baseboard heater. I had origanly purchased one Lasko heater to try in one room. After the great job it did, I purchased three  more of them. I finished up the winter, heating with the Lasko heaters.  I would recommend them to anyone needing a heater. And If I have to replace any one of the heaters I have, it will be with a Lasko 5572 heater.HJ of Missouri', "We were absolutely thrilled with the size and capability of this room heater.  It's a little taller than the other Lasko portable heater and our decision to get it was a good one. For our needs, this one is perfect. ", 'I really enjoy my heater.  I live in Arizona where it is getting cooler at night now.  It is very efficient and quiet.', 'Heats small area immediately in the morning, with an increase of 5-10 degrees in temperature within 15 minutes.  Easy to operate, with remote.  As usual: follow directions in the manufacturers manual for best results!', "Wow, does this put out some heat, and like now..  Don't have to wait for anything to warm up  immediate heat..  2 modes low 900w and high 1500w..  Plus you can set it from 39 degrees to 90 degrees and to kick on automatically if room gets below set temp..  This can almost heat my whole house..  Will prob heat at least 3 rooms.Led readouts are bright and clear, fan, remote, oscillates, has real buttons, not plastic film that will wear out, and stands tall.  Has handle for easy moving.. With gas prices doubling this winter, I'm turning to a space heater so I can lower the thermostat.. ", 'great heater, used it all winter, no problems, good price, fast delivery', "I don't have this exact model, but I have two similar Lesco 1500w heaters w/digital displays w/remotes.  I bought the second one because one of our tenants lost the remote.  One is #5165, the other one is #755320, the only complaint I have on this model is I had to stick a piece of foam tale on the top of the carrying slot in back so my finger wouldn't slip out of the carrying slot when carrying the heater.  The other heater's slot is angled so your fingers don't slip out.  The one remote does control either heater.  I recommended my satisfaction to a friend and he bought one and is happy with it.  I don't know his model #. I've had the first hater 5 yrs and the second one 2 yrs and both work great.", "Great heater. Warms my garage better than expected. I'm not scared to leave it on all night unattended.", "Dose everything it's said it could do"]

column1: Dr. Heater DR966 240-volt Hardwired Shop Garage Commercial Heater
column4: ['The heater requires a 35A circuit with #8AWG wire per Article 424 of the National Electric Code. The heater only pulls 25A on highest setting, but is considered a "fixed" device with a "continuous load", so the wiring and breaker need to be rated at 125%.  That puts it at 31.25A, over a #10AWG wire and 30A breaker\'s rating.  Don\'t risk your insurance company denying your claim if something goes wrong.At that power, you don\'t want to use a line voltage thermostat designed for smaller baseboard heaters.  If you want a wall mounted thermostat, look into any conventional thermostat, a 24VAC HVAC transformer, and a 40A 2-pole 24V HVAC contactor.  I have three DR-966 heaters with their built-in thermostats all the way up and their switches on the 6000W setting, running off a single 24V transformer and Hunter 429999B thermostat, with a contactor near each heater switching the 240V AC on and off.  If I\'m not in the building I keep the thermostat at its minimum 45 degrees setting to prevent pipes from freezing.  Using a contactor, you\'re essentially automating turning the heater on and off, no different than using the instruction manual\'s method of using the circuit breaker, and not voiding any warranty.This is not an infrared heater, the manufacturer calls itself both Dr. Heater and Dr. Infrared Heater.  The heater is a wire coil type, the front two coils are 1500 watts each tied together, the rear coil is a single 3000 watt for a total of 6000 watts.  With the fan blowing on them, a spiral or two of the rear coil may get red, primarily near the coil supports.  If the fan doesn\'t turn the coil will get red hot, and probably break the support wire inside and then droop.  I received one heater that had a bent fan bracket not allowing the blade to turn and when powered up the rear coil did just that.  I received a refund to buy a third heater and since the vendor was filing a damage claim, was told to discard the defective heater if after 10 days the shipping carrier didn\'t contact me to inspect it.  After the 10 days passed without being contacted, I straightened the bracket out, verified the fan worked and then adjusted the drooping rear coil so there was a minimum of red spots.  I ended up with 3 heaters for the price of 2.Although the output of the heaters may feel like no more than a hand held hair dryer when your area is cold, follow the instruction manual\'s recommendations of keeping it the proper distances from walls and other objects.  If you feel it isn\'t putting out like it should, use a clamp-on ammeter to verify the heater is drawing around 25A on each leg with the temperature control fully clockwise and the switch on 6000W.  If it\'s not, contact the vendor.I have a 30x50 pole barn shop with a 10\' ceiling, so the roof peak is about 12\'.  It has "double bubble foil" insulation on the walls and roof, with exposed trusses.  The heater\'s manual recommends 1.25 watts of heating per cubic foot, so 30\' x 50\' x 11\' x 1.25W = 20,625 watts.  With 18,000W of heaters, I can set the thermostat at 60, go to the home store 10 miles away and by the time I get back the heaters have shut off.  If I already have my materials and I\'m in a hurry to get started, I supplement the electrics with a 3-burner 45,000 BTU tank-mounted propane heater to raise the temp to 60 faster.  So a single 6000W heater in an uninsulated 3-car garage may not be adequate.Before I contacted the eBay vendor about the damaged heater, I contacted the Dr. Heater by phone.  They told me they would send a replacement heater and pre-paid shipping label.  Then I received an email stating they would email me a label within one business day and start the replacement process.  I never received the label by email.  When I called Dr. Heater on the second business day they said they would email a label by the end of the day.  I never got that, so I resolved the issue with the eBay vendor, a 10 star solution.  So it may not be worth the stamp to send in your warranty card.  If you get a working unit, it\'s worth the money.  Good luck repairing one later, since parts don\'t seem to be available.  Due to one of mine having a bent fan bracket, if you get a DR-966 in the 160014xx serial number range, stick a screwdriver in the back and try to spin the fan blade before installation.  A pallet of these might have gotten dropped on the dock after coming off a ship from China.  If that bracket was bent before the heater was assembled, then don\'t trust the QC sticker on the back. It hasn\'t got to zero outside yet, and I haven\'t got my first electric bill, so I may be in for a shock in that respect.', "It's an OK heater. You MUST user the heavy 8 gauge wire and the 35 amp circuit breakers that the instructions say. It has a much quieter fan than my old one, so that's a really nice thing. Puts out a good amount of heat for a small heater. So Great so far? The only bad thing that I have to say about it, is the same as a couple other reviews. The thermostat just doesn't work right. It turns on at 65 degrees and cycles on and off like you would expect. But during the day it keeps turning on more and more warming up the shop by turning on at higher and higher temps. By the end of the day it was turning on at 79 degrees and this was with the thermostat not being moved, set the same all day long. So if it had a better thermostat it would easily be a 5 Star heater. Better yet a remote mounted thermostat would be Great! Heats up my well insulated shop 20X16X8 even when it dropped to zero outside. So it's a GREAT heater with a crappy thermostat.         ", 'Installed this heater on a 20 degree day in a dairy milk house ( block building). It had that space up 65 degrees in 20 minutes.This was at the full 6000 watts. Then left the thermostat at 3/4. This was adequate for me. Maybe 70 degrees at full power? A really quality unit for price!', '1000 square foot shop stays warm when it‚Äôs 30 degrees outside. I keep the temp about 58 to 60 when working. Any warmer and it‚Äôs not comfortable. Fairly quite on high.  Great value on a heater. Propane was costly and dangerous in a shop using flammable liquids. ', 'I got this as an open box, but looks brand new.  Got it for a great price.  I have it on a 30 amp breaker with #10 wire.  Seems to work very well with no issues.', 'Nice heater for its size...Puts out a fair amount of heat.Will probably consume a fair amount of electricity if my calculations are right', "This is a well built product at a reasonable price. It is easy to install. It cycles properly and maintains the temperature in my 24'X24' garage. I was expecting more fan noise but it is fairly  quiet.", 'Its a good product for the money', 'Does a good job heating my garage/wood shop.Some mentioned a need to upgrade the electrical capacity. I have a 30 amp breaker with #10 gauge wire. Recommendations are 8 gauge with a 35 amp breaker.I decided to check the amp load of the heater before upgrading. I wired it up and put my clamp meter on both legs at high power. Reading was 21-22 amps per leg. 10 gauge wire is rated for 30 amps. I now run the heater on low when not present in the shop. I switch to high only when I‚Äôm in the shop if necessary.No problems at all. Puts out the heat when I need it.Anyway, I do plan on upgrading wiring and breaker when the weather warms up.Good heater, good price.', "Heater  works great. Its keeping my shop comfortably warm without busting hot air on you like some other heaters I've used."]

column1: New LASKO 760000 Ceramic Heater w Remote
column4: ["this little heater will heat your small room to a toasty comfort level in just minutes, with the remote control everything is a snap and no need to get out of your seat, it is that easy to use, it's compact so it fits anywhere in a room giving you space, this product was a really good price,", "I love this heater. My wife dragged me to Lowe's to by a heater. I told her that we should buy a ceramic heater instead of a infrared heater. But like always she didn't want to listen. We ended up buying a heater for 150. This heater looks like old cast iron heater and it takes like an hour to make a room comfy. BBUUUUTTTT this Lasko heater is the BOMB and very worth it.", "Works like a champ.  This heats my 250 square foot garage that is like an ice cube, otherwise.  I really like the thermostat feature.  I've had two of these in the past, and they have always worked well.", "We have a small house in s.e. mich.. about 700 sq. ft. on the main level.  several years ago our furnace quit and we've been using ceramic heaters ever since.  I bought this lasco heater this fall to see if it could do better than the previous heater and it has been keeping the wholehouseat about 66 to 68 degrees so far.  Right now we are having the coldest below zero weather in years and it is still keeping things at around 60 with no other heater. needless to say, we have turned on an additional ceramic heater and the temp in the living room isaround 65. I repeat we have no other furnace or heater in the housethe basement stays around 60 all the time but as soon as the outdoors temps rise into the 20's and 30's it will be about 68 in here and we will only need the large Lasco heater.I am very happy with this heater.", 'Works well and looks like the picture, but not quite the remote I was looking for.  I understand the remote that actually went with my upright fan, the model is now out of date or for sale.', 'I plugged the space heaters in immediately and it took the chill right off the house love them. I have a heat pump and when the temperature gets below 32 the system needs help. These are perfect.', 'Quiet; Very powerful; Many fan & heat speed/temperature options. Delivered much faster than even my dog\'s favorite (E-bay) dog food! The back of this unit is not even the slightest bit warm, even when temperature and fan speed are at "max"! Greatly helps supplement our home\'s central heat, even during extremely cold weather.', "This heater warms my apartment way better than the heating sytem for the apartment. It's easy to move around and it does not get hot so you can move it without the danger of getting burned bu holding the sides. Good choice for anyone who has to use gas heat or heat a lot. Could save you a lot of money.", 'Actually, my 5/6 year old unit is STILL GOOD. but the remote died from battery corrosion.So, I now have TWO GOOD EXCELLENT HEATERS- with One REMOTE. * works on bothüëçüèª', "This heater provides a great deal of heat for a large room/ recommend it for purchase, if a person is interested a quality heater.....it's well worth the investment/ Thank you."]

column1: Dr Heater USA-Dr. Infrared heater 3000W Greenhouse Garage Workshop Heater
column4: ["Bought this for my workshop in the winter.  It's only 12x12 but has very tall ceilings so I needed something that could heat the space adequately.  The unit is a lot smaller than I thought so that was a plus as it doesn't take up much room.You will need a 220V outlet which I had.  It doesn't heat the room super quick.  I usually turn it on 30 minutes before I'm going to work out there and it's good enough.  Can't expect much more from a unit so small.  The controls work well and so far it seems like a decent unit for the price.", "I originally bought this to heat my wife's greenhouse replacing two milk house heaters. This heater warmed her10x14 greenhouse so well and evenly that we don't need a second heater anymore and she had new growthon plants in the middle of last winter with snow on the ground. I liked it so well I bought another one for my work shop.", 'THE PLUG ABSOLUTELY WOULD NOT FIT INTO A STANDARD USA ELECTRICAL BOX ! ! ! !We really wanted the heater to be ready for the arrival of cold weather, and it was a huge shock to have to deal with re-fitting / re-placing the plug before we could get the heater and our Greenhouse ready.We had to competely replace the plug !     Once the plug had been replaced, it fit perfectly into our Electrician installed electrical box.The heater works really well, and we\'re very pleased with it.   However.... having to deal with a "retro-fit" before we could even get the heater plugged in was very disappointing, and caused quite a delay.', "A lot better than milkbox heaters. Got it late in the season ,Early Feb. I have an uninsulated 10x12 greenhouse and when it got down to 18 it kept it at set 50 degrees.. Didn't run as much as the milkbox unit.  . Havent got my electric bill yet so cant fully rate it and also hasent gone thru Dec. and Jan.", 'Great little heater, plugs into our 20 amp outlet for window ac. Puts out way more heat than our 110 volt infrared heaters, hope its easier on the electric bill??.  Once we have our outside wood boiler hooked up, this little heater will be used in the green house. Great heater for the money.A+A+A+', 'Perfect heater for my small work shop and model train layout.  It puts outmore than enough heat on cold winter days.  Thanks for a great product design.', 'Have not had to use yet but looks good and heats well.  Will know more when gets cold enough to need heat in greenhouse.', 'Works great', 'This heater heats very quickly.  It is designed to heat a greenhouse.']

column1: ProCom ML1PHG 10,000 BTU Infrared VENT FREE HEATER Propane LP Gas
column4: ["Unit has no thermostatic control.  without any control over the temperature, the unit is less controllable than a 3 stage tank top heater (at 1/3 of the price). basically once you light it, it runs until its out of gas or the structure burns down. There don't appear to be any limit or safety devices save an oxygen depletion sensor (which is just a hole in the pilot body).  I would say it was a poor design and a waste of otherwise quality materials.  I am a 30+ year HVAC service and installation contractor.  I would not recommend this product. I will not be installing mine.", "Used it to replace a flame type heater. It's hard to beat infrared heat. Very fast shipping and easy to use. I highly recommend this heater.", 'Like the way its is controlled very easy to use.', "     Received the unit and it needs some kind of regulator to get it to operate. I needed it to heat my garage to work on my 1949 ford P/U. I purchased a new propane gas tank and had it filled at BJs.I am so disappointed with the purchase.    I just took it and threw it down cellar with the two Mr Heater units that won't start...Wendell W Wilkie  ", "I wanted one that would work with a 20 pound tank. Not a 100 pound tank. But you didn't hu.", 'Excellent heater for the price, good quality', 'fittings were loose inside causing it to leak and let gas out in house poorly put together had to get fixed before i could use i will never buy again', 'good heater for the price, works great.', 'good price ,good heater.']

column1: 10 pc American Wick AW-500 Kerosene Heater Wick Fits Many Perfection Models NEW
column4: ['I got these wicks for my antique Perfection kerosene heaters (I bought several more to keep on hand after trying two). In my opinion, this wick actually out-performs the (new old stock) Perfection Brand wicks available for sale, which can be smelly from age, sometimes bent or rusted, and the cotton wick material, itself, tends to be a bit stiff from age, and occasionally are reconditioned or simply moved in the carrier to appear to be new when they are, in fact, used. I\'ve had that result twice from buying "new" old stock Perfection Brand wicks. This American Wick AW-500 fits perfectly, works smoothly, and is made with superior materials and craftsmanship. The wick is all cotton, heavy-duty and is long-lasting. It\'s clean-burning and there is no smoke or odor. The steel wick carrier is sturdy and smooth. Unlike the Perfection Brand wick, the American AW-500 is constructed with 4 splits in the lower part which go into the tank, creating 4 "tails" (NOTE: The lower portion of the wick is not visible in photo, as they are tucked inside its own cylindrical carrier in packaging, and in the photo). The American Wick AW-500 wick is very similar to the Perfection Brand 500 wick, but the Perfection  wick is split in 2 places and has 2 tails. In my opinion, the American AW-500 wick with 4 tails works better and is easier to install, because the 4-way tail split allows the wick tales to be more easily maneuvered around the wick adjuster, to seat a bit lower when turned down, and the tails to dip deeper into the kerosene tank and are more neatly adjusted up and down without binding at all. The cost of this item is very reasonable and I think it\'s a great value, compared with the usually higher-priced original Perfection 500 wicks to be found for sale. I hesitated at first to buy this non-Perfection part for my Perfection heaters, but after a couple of bad experiences with the more costly Perfection wicks, I am so glad I took the chance and bought the American AW-500 wicks! I\'m extremely pleased! I highly recommend this excellent product! ', "These are not very heavy weight, the weave is loose, and they are not even close to the high quality brand name wick I order from England.  Cosmetically it's not nice looking as an original Perfection wick . Heavy metal wick sleeve is good and they are nicely fastened with metal riveting. They will work just fine in a Perfection 500 heater they just don't last as long as the other brand I buy and they will burn down a little bit faster.  If I can get a good deal on an AW-500 wick or this is the only one available it is much better than a fiberglass wick. Just make sure that you are gentle installing the wick and if one gets a lot of tar from contaminated fuel, moisture,  improper use,  and sticky in the wick gallery these will tear. Odor wise they will smell terrible when you burn one in for the first time that is normal because they are not pre charred. If you run at the highest flame setting possible in the Perfection 500  heater burning good quality kerosene they will do a good job. I use a Perfection 500 heater burning clear kerosene every day year round as my only source of heat and for cooking? If I can get a good deal on one or more of these AW500 wicks I will buy them.   ", 'Excellent quality.  AW-45 is lower part of a mechanical wick; AW-40 is the top part only; AW-49 is both top and bottom.  AW-45, as the bottom only, appears to be no longer available from wick manufacturers.  Grab them if you can find them!', 'Fits just as it should. Burns great in my Perfection M525 Heater. Will definitely buy again, although this one will last me for a few years.', 'Much better quality wick than even more expense wicks out there.  This one burns like the OEM all cotton wick with normal  charring as it should.  Other wicks I have used seem to have a high percentage of nylon or other synthetic and leave a hard residue after just one or two burns that is then hard to relight.  This wick has none of that and I will buy buy another just to have one hand. ', "I was skeptical to purchase at first, considering they don't manufacture the Perfection Heaters anymore, but I took a chance and was very happy this wick is quite similar to an original Perfection wick, and it's 100% cotton. The only issue I experienced was that the gear holes on the wick canister didn't exactly line up correctly. Fortunately I was able to transfer the wick to the original wick canister which has gear holes all around it, making it much easier to install.", 'I had to get another one because it had burned down. When I forget to turn off the heater, the wick will burn down one quarter of an inch each time. I probably will be ordering another soon. Thanks for the product and price.', 'Heater is 100yrs. old, was easy to install,glad wick was still available.', 'These were great! I have two 50 year old vintage kerosene heater and these worked out perfectly!! I highly recommend these!', "The next best thing to the 'Perfection' brand wick. Second one I bought. Very dependable."]

column1: Cadet Electric Heater Com-Pak Twin 4,000-Watt 240-Volt Fan-Forced White
column4: ["Installed this unit in a large living room that always seems to have a chill in it.  Was easy to install, seems well built.  The unit is fairly quite, more so then I expected.I like the design of the heating coils.  They are well supported.  The coils on some brands are not and they heat and sag over time which can cause them to short out.  These don't appear to suffer that problem.If you need to zone heat an area, I believe this unit will fill the bill.", 'Easy to install.Had to extend 1 inch beyond wall due to 5" Thickness. Heats Kitchen and den and hallway. Thermostat works great once set never have to touch. Fits in 16 inch centers perfectly. These heaters have a nice firm blast of really warm to hot heat.', 'I have purchased six of these units that I used in my 450 to 575 square foot apartments and they work great. They heat the places quickly and make it cozy warm in no time.', 'This is a jam up heater. Easy to install and heats my entire house. Best purchase ever. Took my gas heater out because of smutting and burnt propane smell. Installed this in an hour. Easy peazy.  I live on the coast in Texas so we have mild winters. This heater is fine for my 1500 square foot home.', 'Cadet has been around for decades.  Well packaged product and clear instructions.  The noise level of the fans is acceptable.  I am using this as aux heat to my ductless heat pump system.', 'Installation was simple, fits between 16" center studs ( 14-1/2" ), chose to solder connections and use wire nut because of amps draw. Fans were not loud and had a strong fan blows out app 4\', I,m heating app 800sf area in middle Tennessee.', 'I use to pre heat my cabin, heats an area 15x18 pretty quick.  Very quiet easy to install', 'American made quality product.  I am using this one to replace the same unit that was over 30 years old.!!  Cadet makes the best and nothing made in China is anyway near as good!~  and the price was OK ,  too!!  If you want quiet, efficient and long lasting heat -- then this is the unit for you!', "I bought this for the garage, 525 sqft. It's not insulated. The double keeps it a comfortable 70 when its low 50s outside. If I insulate, I believe it'll keep it in upper 60s to mid 70s when its 30 something outside. Thermostat cycles as it should.", 'I bought three of these Cadet Twin-Pak heaters. They work great. Very easy to install.I would recommend these heaters to anyone that needs to add heat.']
